Anonymous Mon 01 Nov 2021 00:58:57 No.42816980 Report

>>42816962
One of the biggest differences researchers have found between adults and adolescents is the pre-frontal cortex. This part of the brain is still developing in teens and doesn’t complete its growth until approximately early to mid 20’s. The prefrontal cortex performs reasoning, planning, judgment, and impulse control, necessities for being an adult. Without the fully development prefrontal cortex, a teen might make poor decisions and lack the inability to discern whether a situation is safe. Teens tend to experiment with risky behavior and don’t fully recognize the consequences of their choices.

On the other hand, in adults, the frontal cortex is completely developed. They are able to process and organize information. Adults, who are emotionally and psychologically healthy, are able to judge risky behavior and factor into decision-making the consequences of their choices. Teens might rely more on their amygdala, the part of the brain dealing with emotions, whereas adults rely more on their frontal cortex, leading to balanced thinking and behavior. In fact, another part of the brain that is still developing are certain neural networks of brain cells that link the prefrontal cortex to regions of the brain that are less about reasoning and thinking and more about emotion.

>>42822698
Didn't expect someone to actually be curious enough to ask stuff. I'll go through the questions.
>I can't imagine it being anything more than self induced schizophrenia
Schizophrenia is very different from creating something and talking to it. Schizophrenia is also a disorder, and causes harm to the people that have it. Tulpas are overwhelmingly beneficial.

>I find in unlikely that you'd be able to hallucinate something on a regular basis that is consistent with its mannerisms.
Well when you have them around for an extended period of time they sort of become their own person. They do what they want and you live alongside them. They are people, just like you.

>Does this tulpa have a memory?
Tulpas share the same brain as you, therefore your memories are theirs. if they learn something, then you learn it. If they experience something then you do, by proxy. You can choose to try to mentally distance yourself from them to keep it from being so weird, though.

>If it "experiences" something does it remember it?
You both do, together, as stated previously.

>Has it ever told you anything that surprised you?
In many communities this is considered the benchmark for a tulpa's sentience. When it can surprise you and act independently then you know it's actually a tulpa. The first time I had that happen I was pretty amazed because it felt so foreign, yet familiar. I was overwhelmed and didn't believe it at first, but here I am 10 years later.

I hope that cleared a few things up?
